column96: I had forgotten that my daughter who worked yesterday in a Central London Whitehall office had a pre-planned meeting with a couple of her friends. They went and had a late celebratory birthday dinner. So, today she works from home and can eat it. Yesterday she arrived late due to messed up train schedule which added a late night detour. She has not had her lunch yet, though, it is 1pm soon....so, but I am sure that she will love halloumi. Now, there was plenty of halloumi but I should have opted for some seasonal green vegetables for additional cost.
column98: I think that the salad with the nicely made halloumi slices.....did not really make me feel as if this £25.00 sum was properly spent but one learns.....and nothing wrong with the food .... just it feels that it was not really worth the cost this time or maybe barely. I could have made this salad myself. But the added hummus my daughter will definitely eat, and the mint dip sauce in the other box was nice, there is still plenty of it left, and the oriental flat breads were really nicely done, so nothing to complain either.
column104: This time I felt that I kind of won nothing, pricewise. The food was nicely presented, though, and tasty - so nothing to complain either.

column88: The impression given from the image was of a large portion of food which would feed four people. The crispy cauliflower was shown to have been placed on the curry leading us to expect it to come separately to be added when served. What we received was a very small portion (not even enough for two: and we don't have huge appetites) and the cauliflower was already in the curry so did not remain "crispy". It did taste good though.
column98: If this dish (cauliflower green Thai curry) is to be branded as a family meal, the portion size needs to be improved. I hope we experienced a one-off error: with the food served to us being less than usual. The calories that the dish was supposed to provide suggest that our experience can't have been the norm. Our experience with Bill's chicken schwarma was completely different with plenty of food available, so what we received for the cauliflower green Thai curry was a real shock. The serving size prompted me to complain: the only time I have ever complained about portion sizes for any takeaway ever.
column104: See earlier responses.

They even separate the soup and noodles to keep the noodles from getting soggy, and the vegetables are packed separately as well — something you wouldn't normally expect from a takeaway. Everything was just perfect. I'd say keep up the amazing work; there's no need for improvement because they're already excellent.

column104: Bill's Kingston - include the Thai Green Curry with Chicken, and Thai Green Curry with Tofu into your Dinneroo options again! You sold them while I was completing my first phase of Almased long term plan which meant that I had to postpone the purchases of the abovementioned Dinneroo meal options till later, and when it was time, you discontinued these most healthy meal options which I was so looking forward to ordering/eating. It's a shame. But the Shepherd's Pie option is kind of suitable too [I need to revamp it to make it fully suitable for my Almased meal recipe], so I have been ordering their Shepherd's Pie.   P.S. column87: Dishoom and Banana tree are the only restaurant that actually cater to a family for family dineroo. The other restaurants (Bella Italia, farmer js and many others) simply do not have enough food for a family, the amount of food barely hit 2000 calories for majority of these partners restaurants and the price is very similar to individual portions so they're not really understanding the requirements that it's for a family of 4 minimum. Majority of the food would only be enough for 2 adults to be filled so their parents have to eat less to ensure the kids get enough food for dinner. Dishoom and Banana tree absolutely nails the family dinners because there's enough calories and nutrition and value for money for the entire family. Dishoom and banana tree are high end aswell compared to a lot of these other restaurants and they understand and fulfil the requirements whereas some of these other restaurants are just over priced with small portions like farmer js.
column88: Bella Italias pasta was very dry barely any sauce and small portions. Farmer js portion size is ridiculously small you're better off buying 2 of their individual trays then the family meal. Any restaurant serving under 4000 calories for a family dineroo that caters to a family of 4 should either be removed or change their portion sizes because some of them charge £25 and it's barely enough for 2 people let alone a family.

column96: The portion size wasn't enough. That's all it comes down to for majority of these restaurants. Bella Italia lacked sauce so the pasta was dry. Banana tree and Dishoom are the only ones hitting the mark for size and value. The other restaurants on the list lack calories it's easier for me to just cook at home if these other restaurants can't even provide over 2000 calories for a family dinner it's a bit ridiculous especially for something simple like grains or pasta which are cheap as it is.
column98: Better quality and larger portions.
column104: Deliveroo need to set requirements with partner restaurants for family dineroo to ensure there are enough calories to feed a family of 4 minimum. Every single restaurant needs to take notes from Dishoom and banana tree. Also, Deliveroo need to put the 30% on these restaurants every Wednesday not as a one time per restaurant thing it sort of ruins it because if you've enjoyed a restaurant you want to order again on a Wednesday and enjoy the 30% discount not try somewhere new which isn't as good. If I've ordered a family dineroo from one restaurant and believe it's very good then I look forward to the 30% off on a Wednesday which shouldn't be a one per restaurant offer it should remain because then I could just order it any other day of the week.
